english:
  title: A Remonstrance to the Flower King
  author: Seol Chong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant has heard that when the Flower King first came to this place, he was planted in a fragrant garden and surrounded by emerald curtains. When late spring arrived, he bloomed in splendor, surpassing all other flowers in singular beauty. Then from near and far, all the lovely spirits and youthful blossoms rushed to pay their respects, each fearing to arrive too late.

    Suddenly, a fair maiden appeared—with rosy cheeks and white teeth, bright in her adornment and graceful in her dress. She approached with delicate steps and spoke sweetly: "I have walked upon shores as white as snow, faced seas as clear as mirrors. I have bathed in spring rain to cleanse myself, and enjoyed the cool wind in leisurely wandering. My name is the Rose. Having heard of Your Majesty's noble virtue, I wish to attend upon you in fragrant chambers. Will you receive me?"

    Then came an old man—clothed in rough hemp, belted with leather, his white head leaning on a staff, shuffling forward slowly and bowing low. He spoke: "I dwell beyond the capital, beside the great road. Below, I overlook the vast expanse of wild fields; above, I face the towering heights of distant mountains. My name is the White-Headed Elder. I venture to reflect that though Your Majesty's attendants provide abundantly—rich foods to fill the belly, fine tea and wine to clarify the spirit—there remain needs for restorative medicines to strengthen the vital force and purifying herbs to expel toxins. Thus the ancients said: 'Though silk and hemp have their worth, despise not the humble rush and sedge. All worthy gentlemen prepare for times of want.' Does Your Majesty perhaps share such concerns?"

    One asked, "Since both have come, which will you choose and which reject?" The Flower King replied, "The old man's words hold reason, yet to lose the lovely maiden—how could that be right?"

    Then the old man stepped forward and spoke: "I came believing Your Majesty possessed wisdom and understood righteousness. But I see now I was mistaken. It has ever been rare for rulers not to favor flatterers and sycophants while spurning the upright and true. Thus Mencius remained unrecognized throughout his life, and Feng Tang grew old in minor office. From ancient times it has been so. What can one do?"

    The Flower King answered, "I was wrong. I was wrong."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Flower King likely represents the peony (牡丹), revered in East Asian culture as the 'king of flowers.'
  - key: ''
    value: The Rose and White-Headed Elder represent beauty/pleasure and wisdom/virtue respectively, forming the central moral tension of the piece.
  - key: ''
    value: Mencius and Feng Tang are historical references to virtuous men who were neglected by their rulers, illustrating the danger of favoring flattery over righteousness.
  - key: ''
    value: This work is a didactic allegory employing flower personifications to counsel against preferring courtly pleasures over sage counsel—a common theme in Korean Confucian literature.
